    p #[strong Spectre.css] is designed with consistent design language. You can use your variables to create your new or match an existing design.
      |  All #[strong Sass] variables defined in the #[code src/variables] folder include the #[code !default] flag. You can redefine the variables to override the values.

    p Almost all #[strong Sass] variables have equivalent CSS variables defined in the same naming pattern as #[strong Sass] variables to persist consistency but with an additional customizable 
      +docs-abbr('prefix', '$var-prefix') 
      | . They are used in styles instead of #[strong Sass] variables if possible.

    h5 Good to know:
    ul(style="list-style: none")
      li #[span.text-success ✓] Styles are using CSS variables, except in some cases.
      li #[span.text-success ✓] Sass variables are used mostly only to initialize equivalent CSS variables.
      li #[span.text-success ✓] CSS variable names are being set in the same Sass variable naming pattern for consistency.
      li #[span.text-success ✓] CSS variables are set with an additional customizable prefix.
      li #[span.text-success ✓] There are Sass variables that don't have CSS variables, but they are used in the creation of their names.

      li #[span.text-success ✓] Spectre.css has the first approach to the #[strong Dark] and #[strong light] theme.
      li #[span.text-success ✓] CSS color variables are created from the property values of the dark and light themes.
      li #[span.text-success ✓] Hex color has #[strong four] CSS variables with an additional CSS variable for adjusting color base lightness.
      li #[span.text-success ✓] There are common Sass variable colors for both dark and light themes.
      li #[span.text-success ✓] When changing the values of the base CSS colors, the derived CSS colors change on the fly.
      li #[span.text-success ✓] Colors are being inserted by the #[code color()] function in the #[code hsla] form.
      li #[span.text-success ✓] CSS variable name suffix of the color #[code hue], #[code saturation], #[code lightness], and #[code alpha] are customizable.
      li #[span.text-success ✓] Derived color variables are only used in the background classes and they exist for backward compatibility.

